  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div xml:id="KT13-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">toḻiyiṟ kūṭṭaṅ kūṭṭi āṟṟuvakaiyāṉ āṟṟuvittup piriya vēṟupaṭṭa kiḻatti tōḻikku uraittatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Declared to the confidante by HER who was changed when [he] separated after reassuring [her], he [himself being of] the type who has the strength after having begged the help of the confidante.</p>
          </div>

        <div xml:id="KT13">
            <lg type="edition">
<l>                mācaṟak kaḻīiya yāṉai pōlap</l>
<l>                perumpeya luḻanta virumpiṇart tuṟukaṟ</l>
<l>                paita lorutalai cēkku nāṭa</l>
<l>                ṉōytan taṉaṉē tōḻi</l>
<l>                pacalai yārntaṉa kuvaḷaiyaṅ kaṇṇē.</l>
            </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Pain he gave, friend,</l>
<l>the man from a [mountain] land</l>
<l rend="indent4">who rests in the single cool spot</l>
<l rend="indent">dark, rough, thick stones<note place="foot">Thus, against the usual syntax of imperfective peyareccam clauses connected with <term xml:lang="ta">nāṭaṉ</term> (though possible, of course), the interpretation of Cām. and TVG, justified by the latter with an understanding of the image: the "elephant-stone" served to protect the lovers, because no one will want to rouse a sleeping elephant.</note> that endured great raining</l>
<l rend="indent">like elephants fully washed of dust.</l>
<l>With pallor filled [these] eyes pretty as waterlilies.</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
